Data Analysis of NYC Taxi Trip Data¶

Group 17 : Deepika Chowdary Battula, Laksmi Shivani Reddy, Lakshmi Pranita Kolaganti, Rohini Bandi

OBJECTIVE¶

The objective of the project is to identify the trip duration to travel from one place to another in New York City and plotting the various contributing factors versus trip duration.

PROBLEM STATEMENT¶

To build a machine learning model to predict time duration from NYC taxi trip data set.

Importing Dataset¶

This data set has 1048575 rows which represent approximately 1.5 million taxi trips.There are 11 columns which includes id, vendor_id, date and time (pickup, dropoff), location (pickup, dropoff latitutdes and longitude coordinates), passenger count for all the taxi trips. The data is collected from 2016 January to June.

Data Fields:¶
  1. id - a unique identifier for each trip
  2. vendor_id - a code indicating the provider associated with the trip record
  3. pickup_datetime - date and time when the meter was engaged
  4. dropoff_datetime - date and time when the meter was disengaged
  5. passenger_count - the number of passengers in the vehicle (driver entered value)
  6. pickup_longitude - the longitude where the meter was engaged
  7. pickup_latitude - the latitude where the meter was engaged
  8. dropoff_longitude - the longitude where the meter was disengaged
  9. dropoff_latitude - the latitude where the meter was disengaged
  10. store_and_fwd_flag - This flag indicates whether the trip record was held in vehicle memory before sending to the vendor because the vehicle did not have a connection to the server - Y=store and forward; N=not a store and forward trip.

In [11]:
#calc_distance is a function to calculate distance between pickup and dropoff coordinates using Haversine formula.
def calc_distance(df):
    pickup = (df['pickup_latitude'], df['pickup_longitude'])
    drop = (df['dropoff_latitude'], df['dropoff_longitude'])
    return haversine(pickup, drop)

#Select all the features in X array
import statsmodels.api as sm
X_opt = X1[:,range(0,46)]
regressor_OLS = sm.OLS(endog = Y, exog = X_opt).fit()

#Fetch p values for each feature
p_Vals = regressor_OLS.pvalues

#define significance level for accepting the feature.
sig_Level = 0.05

#Loop to iterate over features and remove the feature with p value less than the sig_level
while max(p_Vals) > sig_Level:
    print("Probability values of each feature \n")
    print(p_Vals)
    X_opt = np.delete(X_opt, np.argmax(p_Vals), axis = 1)
    print("\n")
    print("Feature at index {} is removed \n".format(str(np.argmax(p_Vals))))
    print(str(X_opt.shape[1]-1) + " dimensions remaining now... \n")
    regressor_OLS = sm.OLS(endog = Y, exog = X_opt).fit()
    p_Vals = regressor_OLS.pvalues
    print("=================================================================\n")
    
#Print final summary
print("Final stat summary with optimal {} features".format(str(X_opt.shape[1]-1)))

#Find linear correlation of each feature with the target variable
from scipy.stats import pearsonr
df1 = pd.DataFrame(np.concatenate((X_train,y_train.reshape(len(y_train),1)),axis=1))
df1.columns = df1.columns.astype(str)

features = df1.iloc[:,:46].columns.tolist()
target = df1.iloc[:,46].name

correlations = {}
for f in features:
    data_temp = df1[[f,target]]
    x1 = data_temp[f].values
    x2 = data_temp[target].values
    key = f + ' vs ' + target
    correlations[key] = pearsonr(x1,x2)[0]
    
data_correlations = pd.DataFrame(correlations, index=['Value']).T
data_correlations.loc[data_correlations['Value'].abs().sort_values(ascending=False).index]

All the estimated times are calculated to travel from one zone of New York city to another zone. Data exploration and variable analysis is a very important aspect. we also cleaned the data while exploring as there were some outliers. We did feature engineering to filter and gather only the optimal features. Then we finally trained the models on the optimal features.
